{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"345131b8-aec0-4359-aa4c-f208e3c21b68","content":"In .NET MAUI, you use the **lifecycle mapping** API in `MauiProgram.cs` (or your app builder setup) to hook platform events without touching platform projects directly:\n\n```csharp\nbuilder.ConfigureLifecycleEvents(events =>\n{\n#if ANDROID\n    events.AddAndroid(android => android\n        .OnPause(activity => { /* runs on Android pause */ })\n        .OnStop(activity => { /* runs on Android stop */ }));\n#endif\n\n#if IOS\n    events.AddiOS(ios => ios\n        .DidEnterBackground(app => { /* runs on iOS background */ }));\n#endif\n});\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- Add `using Microsoft.Maui.LifecycleEvents;` at the top.\n- Platform-specific blocks are guarded by `#if` directives so they only compile for the target platform.\n- The delegates receive the native object (`Activity` on Android, `UIApplication` on iOS), giving you full access to the platform API if needed.\n- You can also hook `OnRestart`/`OnResume` (Android) and `WillEnterForeground` (iOS) for the reverse transition.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"c644f870-7bc2-4042-bc98-8dbc04262b74","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to hook into platform-specific lifecycle events in .NET MAUI — specifically Android's `OnPause`/`OnStop` and iOS's `DidEnterBackground`. This is a general knowledge question, not a code task in the repository.","outputTokens":359,"requestId":"142C:29F7F6:6A18D03:726E090:6A03CCAF"},"id":"ec290b52-4f0d-4eb7-a296-1e4ac7ab810f","timestamp":"2026-05-13T00:58:31.703Z","parentId":"e36f2650-7115-4d71-8040-98e179e0b8f5"}
